..SUBPART
1.3   [ASBESTOS

  Remove, handle, and dispose of asbestos in accordance with Section
  \=02080=\, "Removal and Disposal of Asbestos Materials."]

..SUBPART
1.4   [POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYLS (PCB) CONTROL

  Remove, handle, and dispose of PCBs in accordance with Section \=16012=\,
  "Removal of PCB Insulated Transformers."]

..SUBPART
1.5   WASTE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND HAZARDOUS WASTE (WHM/HW) DISPOSAL:

  Remove and dispose of WHM/HW in accordance with Section \=02082=\.

..SUBPART
1.6   DEFINITIONS

..SUBPART
1.6.1   Sediment

  Soil and other debris that have eroded and have been transported by runoff
  water or wind.

..SUBPART
1.6.2   Solid Waste

  Rubbish, debris, garbage, and other discarded solid materials, except
  hazardous waste as defined in the paragraph entitled, "Hazardous Waste,"
  resulting from industrial, commercial, and agricultural operations and from
  community activities.

..SUBPART
1.6.3   Rubbish

  Combustible and noncombustible wastes such as paper, boxes, glass,
  crockery, metal, lumber, cans, and bones.

..SUBPART
1.6.4   Debris

  Combustible and noncombustible wastes such as ashes and waste materials
  resulting from construction or maintenance and repair work, leaves, and
  tree trimmings.

..SUBPART
1.6.5   Chemical Waste

  This includes salts, acids, alkalies, herbicides, pesticides, and organic
  chemicals.

..SUBPART
1.6.6   Sanitary Wastes

..SUBPART
1.6.6.1   Sewage

  Waste characterized as domestic sanitary sewage.

..SUBPART
1.6.6.2   Garbage

  Refuse and scraps resulting from preparation, cooking, dispensing, and
  consumption of food.

..SUBPART
1.6.7   Hazardous Waste

  Hazardous substances as defined in \-40 CFR 261-\ or as defined by
  applicable State and local regulations.

..SUBPART
1.6.8   Oily Waste

  Petroleum products and bituminous materials.

..SUBPART
1.7   SUBMITTALS

..SUBPART
1.7.1   \*SD-56, Record of Existing Conditions

  [Preconstruction Survey Report:  Submit [three] [_____] copies of the
  preconstruction survey report.*\]

..SUBPART
1.7.2   \*SD-62, Work Plan

  [Environmental Protection Plan:  Submit [four] [_____] copies of the
  proposed environmental protection plan.*\]

..SUBPART
1.7.3   \*SD-70, Test Reports

  [Laboratory Analysis:  Submit a copy of an approved laboratory analysis of
  materials collected as a result from sandblasting or abrasive blasting
  operations before disposing of waste materials.*\]

..SUBPART
1.7.4   \*SD-91, Records

  [Solid Waste Disposal Permit:  Submit one copy of a [State] [and][local]
  permit or license showing such [agency's] [agencies'] approval of the
  disposal plan.]

  [Disposal Permit for Hazardous Waste:  Submit a copy of the applicable EPA
  [and State] permit[s] or license[s] for transportation, treatment, storage,
  and disposal of hazardous waste by permitted facilities.]

  [Sediment and Erosion Control Plan Approval:  Submit one copy of Maryland's
  Department of the Environment notice of approval of the sediment and
  erosion control plan submitted to the State of Maryland as required in the
  paragraph entitled, "Sediment and Erosion Control Plan."*\]

..SUBPART
1.8   ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION REQUIREMENTS

  Provide and maintain during the life of the contract, environmental
  protection as defined.  Plan for and provide environmental protective
  measures to control pollution that develops during normal construction
  practice.  Plan for and provide environmental protective measures required
  to correct conditions that develop during the construction of permanent or
  temporary environmental features associated with the project.  Comply with
  Federal, State, and local regulations (including \-COE EP-1165-2-\) pertaining
  to the environment, including but not limited to water, air, and noise
  pollution.                                                                  

..SUBPART
1.8.1   Environmental Protection Plan

  \*SD-91, Five days after the award of contract, the Contractor shall meet
  with the Contracting Officer to discuss the proposed environmental
  protection plan and to develop mutual understanding relative to the details
  of environmental protection, including measures for protecting natural
  resources, required reports, and other measures to be taken.*\

..SUBPART
1.8.1.1   Environmental Planning Report

  Fourteen days after meeting with the Contracting Officer, the Contractor
  shall submit to the Contracting Officer the proposed environmental plan for
  further discussion, review, and approval.

..SUBPART
1.8.1.2   Commencement of Work

  \*SD-91, As directed by the Contracting Officer following approval.*\

..SUBPART
1.8.2   Preconstruction Survey

  \*SD-56, Perform a preconstruction survey of the project site with the
  Contracting Officer, and take photographs showing existing environmental
  conditions in and adjacent to the site.*\

..SUBPART
1.8.3   Operational Limits

  There shall be no discharge of excavation ground water, fuels or chemicals
  to the sanitary sewer, storm drains or to the river without the prior spe
  cific authorization of the Environmental Programs Division in writing.

..SUBPART
1.8.3.1   Runoff

  Construction site runoff shall be prevented from entering any storm sewer
  or the river directly by the use of straw bales or another method suitable
  to the Environmental Programs Division.

..SUBPART
1.8.3.2   Fuel Tanks

  On site fuel tanks must be over drip pans and the tanks and drip pans must
  be covered during inclement weather and when work is not in progress at the
  site.

..PART
PART 2   PRODUCTS

  Not Applicable

..PART
PART 3   EXECUTION

..SUBPART
3.1   PROTECTION OF NATURAL RESOURCES

  Preserve the natural resources within the project boundaries and outside
  the limits of permanent work.  Restore to an equivalent or improved
  condition upon completion of work.  Confine construction activities to
  within the limits of the work indicated or specified.

..SUBPART
3.1.1   Land Resources

  Except in areas to be cleared, do not remove, cut, deface, injure, or
  destroy trees or shrubs without the Contracting Officer's permission.  Do
  not fasten or attach ropes, cables, or guys to existing nearby trees for
  anchorages, unless specifically authorized by the Contracting Officer.
  Where such use of attach ropes, cables, or guys is authorized, the
  Contractor shall be responsible for any resultant damage.

..SUBPART
3.1.1.1   Protection

  Protect existing trees which are to remain and which may be injured,
  bruised, defaced, or otherwise damaged by construction operations.  Remove
  displaced rocks from uncleared areas.  Remove by approved excavation, trees
  with 30 percent or more of their root systems destroyed.

..SUBPART
3.1.1.2   Replacement

  Remove trees and other landscape features scarred or damaged by equipment
  operations, and replace them with equivalent, undamaged trees and landscape
  features.  \*SD-91, Obtain the Contracting Officer's approval before
  replacement.*\

..SUBPART
3.1.1.3   Temporary Construction

  Remove traces of temporary construction facilities such as haul roads, work
  areas, structures, foundations of temporary structures, stockpiles of
  excess or waste materials, and other signs of construction.  Grade
  temporary roads, parking areas, and similar temporarily used areas to
  conform with surrounding contours.

..SUBPART
3.1.2   [Water Resources

..SUBPART
3.1.2.1   Stream Crossings

  \*SD-91, The Contracting Officer's approval is required before equipment is
  allowed to ford live streams.*\  In areas where frequent crossings are
  required, install temporary culverts or bridges.  Remove these temporary
  culverts or bridges upon completion of work, and repair the area [to its
  original condition] [or] [as indicated] [or] [as specified].

..SUBPART
3.1.2.2   Oily Wastes

  Prevent oily or other hazardous substances from entering the ground,
  drainage areas, or local bodies of water.  Temporary fuel oil or
  petroleum storage tanks shall be provided with a catch pan of sufficient
  size and strength to contain the contents of the tanks in the event of
  leakage or spillage.

..SUBPART
3.1.3   Fish and Wildlife Resources

  Do not disturb fish and wildlife.  \*SD-31, Do not alter water flows or
  otherwise significantly disturb the native habitat adjacent to the project
  and critical to the survival of fish and wildlife, except as indicated or
  specified.*\]

..SUBPART
3.2   HISTORICAL AND ARCHEOLOGICAL RESOURCES

  \*SD-91, Carefully preserve and report immediately to the Contracting
  Officer items having possible historical or archeological interest which
  are discovered in the course of work under this contract.*\  Protect
  monuments, markers, and works of art.

..SUBPART
3.3   SEDIMENT AND EROSION CONTROL MEASURES

..SUBPART
3.3.1   Burnoff

  Burnoff of the ground cover is not permitted.

..SUBPART
3.3.2   [Borrow Pit Areas

  Manage and control borrow pit areas to prevent sediment from entering
  nearby streams or lakes.  Restore areas, including those outside the borrow
  pit, disturbed by borrow and haul operations.  Restoration includes
  grading, replacement of topsoil, and establishment of a permanent
  vegetative cover.  Uniformly grade side slopes of borrow pit to not more
  than a slope of one part vertical to two parts horizontal.  Uniformly grade
  the bottom of the borrow pits to provide a flat bottom, and drain by
  outfall ditches or other suitable means.  Stockpile topsoil removed during
  the borrow pit operation, and replace topsoil as part of restoring the
  borrow pit area.]

..SUBPART
3.3.3   [Protection of Erodible Soils

  Immediately finish the earthwork brought to a final grade, as indicated or
  specified.  Immediately protect the side slopes and back slopes upon
  completion of rough grading.  Plan and conduct earthwork in such a manner
  so as to minimize the duration of exposure of unprotected soils.]

..SUBPART
3.3.4   Temporary Protection of Erodible Soils

  Use the following methods to prevent erosion and control sedimentation:

..SUBPART
3.3.4.1   Mechanical Retardation and Control of Runoff

  Mechanically retard and control the rate of runoff from the construction
  site.  This includes construction of diversion ditches, benches, and berms
  to retard and divert runoff to protected drainage courses.

..SUBPART
3.3.4.2   [Sediment Basins

  Trap sediment in [temporary] [permanent] sediment basins.  [Select a basin
  size to accommodate the runoff of a local [_____]-year storm.]  Pump dry,
  and remove the accumulated sediment after each storm.  Use a paved weir or
  vertical overflow pipe for overflow.  Remove collected sediment from the
  site.  Institute effluent quality monitoring programs.]

..SUBPART
3.3.4.3   [Borrow

  This is permitted only in areas where suitable environmental controls are
  possible.]

..SUBPART
3.3.4.4   Vegetation, Mulch, and Seeding

  Provide temporary protection on sides and back slopes as soon as rough
  grading is completed or sufficient soil is exposed to require erosion
  protection.  Protect slopes by accelerated growth of permanent vegetation,
  temporary vegetation, mulching, or netting.  Stabilize slopes by
  hydroseeding, anchoring mulch in place, covering with anchored netting,
  sodding, or such combination or these and other methods necessary for
  effective erosion control.  Provide new seeding where ground is disturbed.
  Include topsoil or nutriment during the seeding operation as necessary to
  [establish] [reestablish] a suitable stand of grass.  [The seeding
  operation shall be as specified in Section \=_____=\, "__________."]

..SUBPART
3.4   CONTROL AND DISPOSAL OF SOLID AND SANITARY WASTES

  Pick up solid wastes, and place in containers which are regularly emptied.
  Do not prepare, cook, or dispose of food on the project site.  Prevent
  contamination of the site and other areas when handling and disposing
  wastes.  On completion, leave the areas clean.  Control and dispose of
  waste.

..SUBPART
3.4.1   Disposal of Rubbish and Debris

  Dispose of rubbish and debris in accordance with the requirements
  specified.

..SUBPART
3.4.1.1   [Removal From Government Property

  Remove and dispose rubbish and debris from Government property.]

  [Removal to Existing Borrow Pit

  Haul rubbish and debris to the borrow pit indicated or specified, and cover
  with a minimum of 2 feet of soil after completing rubbish and debris
  deposition, as directed.  Excavate sufficient soil for coverage before
  depositing waste.  Begin dumping in one area of the pit, and fill to a
  height such that when 2 feet of soil is added, the finished contours blend
  with those of adjacent areas.]

  [Removal to Borrow Pit

  Haul rubbish and debris to the borrow pit being utilized for this contract,
  and dispose of in the void created by excavation for borrow material.
  Excavate sufficient soil to provide a minimum of 2 feet of cover over the
  deposited rubbish and debris.  Grade and restore area as specified in
  Section \=02221=\, "Earthwork for Structures and Pavements."  Begin dumping
  in one area of the pit, and fill to a height such that when [2][____] feet
  of soil are added, finished contours blend with those of adjacent areas.]

..SUBPART
3.4.2   [Garbage Disposal

  Place garbage in approved containers; the Government will provide pickup
  and disposal service.]

  [Place garbage in approved containers, and move to a pickup point or
  disposal area, where directed.]

..SUBPART
3.4.3   Sewage, Odor, and Pest Control

  Dispose of sewage through connection to [a] [municipal[,]] [district[,]]
  [or] [station] sanitary sewage system[s].  Where such system[s] [is] [are]
  not available, use chemical toilets or comparably effective units, and
  periodically empty wastes into [a] [municipal[,]] [district[,]] [or]
  [station] sanitary sewage system[s], or construct and maintain an approved
  type of adequate sanitary convenience for the use of persons employed on
  the work in accordance with the paragraph entitled, "Sanitation," of
  Section \=01010=\, "General Paragraphs."  Include provisions for pest
  control and elimination of odors.

..SUBPART
3.5   CONTROL AND DISPOSAL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE
             
  Dispose of waste hazardous waste and hazardous waste (WHW/HW) shall be in
  accordance with Section \=02082=\.

..SUBPART
3.5.1   Hazardous Waste

  Store hazardous waste in approved containers (\-49 CFR 178-\) DOT properly
  labeled to identify the type of waste and the date the container was
  filled.  Remove the containers from the project site, and store and dispose
  of hazardous waste in accordance with \-40 CFR 260-\, \-40 CFR 263-\ [,]
  [and] \-40 CFR 264-\ [and] [\-VDWM-\].  For oil and hazardous material
  spills, notify the Contracting Officer immediately.

..SUBPART
3.5.1.1   Petroleum Products

  Conduct the fueling and lubricating of equipment and motor vehicles so as
  to protect against spills and evaporation.  Dispose of lubricants to be
  discarded and all excess oil.

..SUBPART
3.5.1.2   Lead Battery Electrolyte

  Dispose of electrolyte solution from lead-acid batteries in accordance
  with Federal, state and local regulations.  See Section \=02082=\ and
  \-NEPSS-PS-015-\.

..SUBPART
3.6   DUST CONTROL

  Keep dust down at all times, including during nonworking periods.
  Sprinkle or treat with dust suppressants the soil at the site, haul roads,
  and other areas disturbed by operations.  Dry power brooming is not
  permitted.  Instead, use vacuuming, wet mopping, wet sweeping, or wet power
  brooming.  Air blowing is permitted only for cleaning nonparticulate debris
  such as steel reinforcing bars.  Only wet cutting is permitted for cutting
  concrete blocks, concrete, and bituminous concrete.  Do not unnecessarily
  shake bags of cement, concrete mortar, or plaster.

..SUBPART
3.6.1   Sandblasting

  Provide tarpaulin drop cloths and windscreens under and around
  sandblasting operations to confine and collect dust, sand, paint, and other
  debris for disposal in accordance with the requirements specified.

..SUBPART
3.6.2   Abrasive Blasting

  Provide tarpaulin drop cloths and windscreens to enclose abrasive blasting
  operations to confine and collect dust, abrasive agent, paint chips, and
  other debris.  [Perform work involving removal of hazardous material in
  accordance with \-29 CFR 1910.94-SUBPART G-\.]  [Dispose of abrasive
  blasting waste containing [lead] [and] [_____] in accordance with
  \-40 CFR 262-\, \-40 CFR 263-\, and \-40 CFR 264-\.]  [Dispose of
  nonhazardous abrasive blasting debris in accordance with the paragraph
  entitled, "Disposal of Rubbish and Debris."]

..SUBPART
3.6.3   Disposal Requirements

  Collect dust, sand, paint, and other debris resulting from sandblasting
  operations and store in 55-gallon drums with watertight lids.  Take a
  representative sample of this material, and test for extraction procedure
  (EP) toxicity with respect to lead, chromium, and cadmium content.  The
  sampling and testing shall be performed in accordance with \-40 CFR 261-\.
  [Handle debris resulting from the sandblasting operations as a hazardous
  material, and dispose of in accordance with \-40 CFR 262-\, \-40 CFR 263-\,
  and \-40 CFR 264-\.  Meet all applicable requirements in this process.
  Transport hazardous material only by a transporter licensed and permitted
  for transportation of hazardous materials.  Dispose of hazardous material
  in an EPA-approved and -permitted facility specifically designated for
  hazardous waste disposal.]

..SUBPART
3.7   NOISE

  Make the maximum use of low-noise emission products, as certified by the
  EPA.  Blasting or use of explosives is not permitted without written
  permission from the Contracting Officer, and then only during designated
  times.  [Confine pile-driving operations to the period between 8 a.m. and 4
  p.m., Monday through Friday, exclusive of holidays, unless otherwise
  specified.]

..SUBPART
3.8   HAZARDOUS WASTE GENERATION

  Handle generated hazardous waste in accordance with \-40 CFR 262-\.

..SUBPART
3.9   HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL

  Dispose of hazardous waste in accordance with \-40 CFR 263-\ and
  \-40 CFR 264-\.

     -- End of Section --
